Europe needs to restart immigration.
Brussels - More than 900 migrants who attempted to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
At the same time, rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching for a safe port where passengers can disembark throughout the summer.
The refugee and migrant camps on the Greek island of Lesbos are overcrowded, and the conditions are similar in other Libyan reception centers.
Turkey has torn up the 2016 agreement to block migrants from entering the EU.
Despite European countries hoping to help immigrants, they also respect international law, but they don't want overcrowding.
The number of immigrants and refugees pouring into the EU in 2015-16 surged — many of them seeking to flee Syria's war fires — which greatly affected trust within the EU.
The massive influx of immigrants eroded the government's confidence in managing the external borders and refugee affairs of the EU, and it highlighted the futility of cooperation with the countries of origin of immigrants.
Therefore, immigration became a political football, a delicacy of populists.
Under the leadership of President von der Leyen, the new EU commission must regain control of the immigration issue while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
For this, the EU needs to re-draft policies in four aspects, mobilizing member states to act for European interests.
The EU must first ensure the urgent security of its external borders, which is a prerequisite for maintaining open internal borders.
Any country in which people can freely move within, including the US, India, China, Switzerland and Russia, will not outsource the control of external borders to a state or region.
Controlling the EU's external borders must be a collective task and a national task.
The EU Border and Coast Guard agency Frontex must be further strengthened and should be deployed with joint patrols — including coastlines and airports — by member states.
The EU must also relaunch Operation Sophia to tackle illegal migration in the Mediterranean.
Secondly, Europe needs to deal with economic migrants and those seeking asylum separately.
Mixing them together has led to the asylum system on the brink of collapse; dealing with them separately will enable migrants who are worried about their lives to be heard while their rights are protected.
Solving the EU's true economic and social needs requires effective blue card or green card policies for economic migrants, along with a general immigration target.
This cannot be put off until the next migration crisis to consider introducing these mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break through the taboo.
Firstly, the number of economic migrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a common interest issue.
Secondly, policies must clearly indicate which migrants are welcome.
Thirdly, member states must answer which EU help is needed to achieve a smooth immigration process.
Lastly, visas and work permits must be put on the table to facilitate the return of illegal immigrants to their countries of origin.
Indeed, according to EU treaties, each member state needs to manage immigrants coming from outside the EU itself.
However, if the government reaches an agreement on the overall target of EU immigrants, it would be a huge step forward.
Conversely, member states can provide the desired country of origin of economic immigrants and specific requirements, as well as the EU budget resources needed to accommodate them.
In this way, the right to immigrate would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has already established an active immigration policy, selecting immigrants through indicators such as country of origin, skill level, and age level.
Europe can do that too.
Thirdly, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
Firstly, the mandatory allocation of asylum seekers within the EU must be abolished.
This requirement has destroyed the atmosphere within the EU, but if the borders, asylum, and migration system is fully effective, it could still be feasible.
Moreover, we cannot expect the EU's frontline member states to solve the issue of illegal migrants crossing external borders on their own.
Refugee camps are already overcrowded, and migrants are subjected to abuse by the authorities, or forced further north.
The responsibility of the first member state the migrants arrive in must be supplemented by the cohesion of the European Union.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to smooth out the behavior and management capabilities of national asylum institutions.
Only in this way can national decisions be respected throughout the Schengen area, ensuring the integrity of the border travel zone.
After smoothing out the behavior and management capabilities of national asylum institutions, the asylum application process can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should build a stronger win-win cooperation with the source country and transit country.
These connections are crucial to repatriate immigrants who are prohibited by law from entering the EU.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic tools, including development assistance and investment funds, as well as plans for security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's immigration targets, as well as skills cooperation to prepare for European work positions, can be provided to third countries that yearn for stable diaspora remittances.
At the same time, the EU must address the root cause of immigration.
Included in this are population explosions in sub-Saharan Africa; climate changes impacting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; racial conflicts; and a shortage of job opportunities.
EU aid should focus on rebuilding stability and reducing risks through supporting security, community resilience, and good governance.
Success in this area would make investments more secure, release private and domestic finance, thereby achieving national economic growth, job creation, and alternative solutions to migration.
The new European Commission has the opportunity to move the EU away from a subconscious reaction to the migration crisis and towards a more consistent and sustainable policy, both internally and externally.
We cannot miss this opportunity.
